The party has performed better in local elections; they are in control of 31<!--29 from 2007, gaining two in 2008 (see BBC and Lib Dem refs)--> councils.<ref name="2008localcouncils">{{cite web|year =2008|url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7328224.stm|title = Lib Dems launch councils campaign|publisher =[[BBC]]|accessdate =2008-04-03}}</ref> In the [[United Kingdom local elections, 2008|2008 local elections]] they gained 25% of the vote (ahead of Labour), increasing their control by 34 to more than 4200 council seats (21%).<ref name="libdem2008local">{{cite web|year =2008|url =http://www.libdems.org.uk/home/elections-2008-results-summary-61340;show|title =Elections 2008: results summary|publisher =Liberal Democrats|accessdate =2008-09-22}}</ref> 

===European elections===
[[Image:Graham Watson MEP.JPG|thumb|[[Graham Watson]]: Former leader of the [[Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe]] is the Liberal Democrat MEP for the South West of England and the first Lib Dem to be elected to the European parliament]]
The party has generally not performed as well in elections to the [[European Parliament]]. In the [[United Kingdom local elections, 2004|2004 local elections]], their share of the vote was 29% (placing them second, ahead of Labour)<ref name="2004localelection">{{cite web|year =2004|url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/3797049.stm|title =Lib Dems hail three-party contest|publisher =[[BBC]]|accessdate =2008-03-21}}</ref> and 14.9% in the simultaneous [[European Parliament Election 2004|European Parliament elections]] (putting them in fourth place behind [[United Kingdom Independence Party]] (UKIP)).<ref name="2004euroelection">{{cite web|year =2004|url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/in_depth/uk_politics/2004/vote_2004/|title =Vote 2004|publisher =[[BBC]]|accessdate =2008-03-21}}</ref>  The results of the [[European Parliament election, 2009 (United Kingdom)|2009 European elections]] were similar with the party achieving a vote of 28% in the county council elections yet achieving only 13.7% in the Europeans despite the elections taking place on the same day.  The 2009 elections did however see the party gain one seat from UKIP in the East Midlands region taking the number of representatives in the parliament up to 11. <ref>{{cite web|year =2009|url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/shared/bsp/hi/elections/euro/09/html/ukregion_31.stm|title=European Election 2009: East Midlands|publisher =[[BBC]]|accessdate =2009-06-08}}</ref>

In Europe the party sits with the [[Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe]] (ALDE) which favours further deepening and enlargement of the EU.<ref>{{cite web|year =2009|url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/8011001.stm#liberal|title=Groups in the European Parliament|publisher =[[BBC]]|accessdate =2009-06-08}}</ref>  The groups leader for seven and a half years was the South West of England MEP [[Graham Watson]] who was also the first Liberal Democrat to be elected to the European parliament when he won the old Somerset and North Devon constituency in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|year =2009|url =http://www.alde.eu/en/about-us/leader/|title=Biographical details: Graham Watson MEP, Former leader of the Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe in the European Parliament|publisher =[[ALDE]]|accessdate =2009-06-08}}</ref>  The groups current leader is the former Belgian prime minister [[Guy Verhofstadt]].<ref>[http://www.alde.eu/en/details/news/guy-verhofstadt-elected-unopposed-as-new-alde-group-leader/ ALDE | Guy Verhofstadt elected unopposed as new ALDE group leader]</ref>

