===Scottish Parliament elections===
[[Image:Tavish Scott MSP at Bournemouth.jpg|thumb|[[Tavish Scott]]: Leader of the Scottish Liberal Democrats]]
The first elections for the [[Scottish parliament]] were held in 1997 and resulted in the Liberal Democrats forming a [[coalition government]] with Labour from its establishment until 2007;<ref name="1999-2007scotland">{{cite web|year =2007|url =http://www.institute-of-governance.org/onlinepub/election2007_devolutionofage.html|title =Election 2007 <U+2013> Devolution Come of Age?|publisher =Institute of Governance|accessdate =2008-03-21}}</ref> the Liberal Democrat leader [[Jim Wallace]] became [[Deputy First Minister of Scotland|Deputy First Minister]] a role he continued until his retirement as party leader in 2005.  The new leader of the party, [[Nicol Stephen]] then took on the role of [[Deputy First Minister of Scotland|Deputy First Minister]] until the election of [[Scottish Parliament election, 2007|2007]]<ref name="nicolstephen">{{cite web|year = 2005|url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/4122106.stm|title =Lib Dems choose Stephen as leader|publisher =[[BBC]]|accessdate =2008-03-28}}</ref>

Since the parliament was established, the Lib Dems have maintained a consistent number of MSP's.  From 17 initially elected, they retained this number in 2003 and went down one to 16 in 2007.<ref name="scottishparliament">{{cite web|year = 2007|url =http://election.theherald.co.uk/results/|title =Holyrood Results|publisher =[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]]|accessdate =2008-05-08}}</ref>.  The current leader of the [[Scottish Liberal Democrats]] is the MSP for [[Shetland]], [[Tavish Scott]] who took up his role in 2008.<ref>[http://www.politics.co.uk/news/legal-and-constitutional/tavish-scott-becomes-scottish-lib-dem-leader-$1237933.htm Politics.co.uk - Scottish Lib Dems choose new leader]</ref>

