===Welsh Assembly Elections===
[[Image:Kirsty Williams AM at Harrogate.jpg|thumb|[[Kirsty Williams]]: Leader of the Welsh Liberal Democrats]]
Elections to the newly created [[National Assembly for Wales|Welsh assembly]] also took place for the first time in 1999 and saw the Liberal Democrats take 6 seats in the inaugural assembly with the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] winning the majority of seats in the assembly but not enough to win an outright majority.  In October 2000 following a series of close votes the parties formed a [[Lib-Lab Pact|coalition]] which saw the Lib Dem leader in the assembly [[Michael German]] become the Deputy First Secretary.<ref>{{cite web|year =2000|url =http://www.guardian.co.uk/politics/2000/oct/16/wales.devolution |title=Lib Dems agree Welsh Assembly power deal|publisher =[[The Guardian]]|accessdate =2009-06-09}}</ref>  The deal lasted until the election of 2003 when Labour won enough seats to be able to govern outright.<ref name="2003waleselection">{{cite web|year =2003|url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/3007665.stm|title =Morgan pledges to govern alone|publisher =[[BBC]]|accessdate =2008-03-21}}</ref> 

The party has polled consistently in all three elections to the assembly so far returning six representatives each time establishing themselves as the fourth party in [[Wales]] behind Labour, the Conservatives and [[Plaid Cymru]].  The current leader of the [[Welsh Liberal Democrats]] is [[Kirsty Williams]] the assembly member for [[Brecon & Radnorshire]], the assembly's first female leader.<ref>{{cite web|year =2008|url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/wales/7771745.stm|title =Williams election breaks mould|publisher =[[BBC]]|accessdate =2009-06-09}}</ref>

