==Structure==
The Liberal Democrats are a [[Federation|federal]] party of the parties of Wales, Scotland and England. Scotland and England are further split into regional parties. The parliamentary parties of the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]], the [[House of Lords]], the [[Scottish Parliament]] and [[Welsh Assembly]] form semi-autonomous units within the party. The leaders in the House of Commons and the Scottish Parliament are the leaders of the federal party and the Scottish Party; the leaders in the other two chambers, and the officers of all parliamentary parties, are elected from their own number. The Lib Dems had around 73,000 members in 2004,<ref name="financialstatement">{{cite web|year =2004|url =http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0010/58519/Liberal-Democrats-Statement-of-Accounts-2007.pdf|format=PDF|title =Reports and Financial Statements |publisher =[[Electoral Commission (United Kingdom)]]|accessdate =2008-09-22}}</ref> and in the first quarter of 2008, the party received [[GDP|<U+00A3>]]1.1 million in donations and have total borrowings and unused credit facilities of <U+00A3>1.1 million (the "total debt" figure reported by the Electoral Commission includes, for example, unused overdraft facilities). This compares to Labour's <U+00A3>3.1 million in donations and <U+00A3>17.8 million of borrowing/credit facilities, and the Conservatives' <U+00A3>5.7 million in donations and <U+00A3>12.1 million of borrowing/credit facilities.<ref name="2008finances">{{cite web|year = 2008|url =http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/news-and-media/news-releases/electoral-commission-media-centre/news-releases-donations/new-figures-published-showing-political-parties-donations-and-borrowings|title =New figures published showing political parties' donations and borrowing|publisher =[[Electoral Commission (United Kingdom)]]|accessdate =2008-09-22}}</ref> In 2005, the party received a donation of <U+00A3>2.4 million from businessman [[Michael Brown (Liberal Democrats donor)|Michael Brown]], the largest single donation in its history.<ref>{{cite web|year=2005|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,2-1793681,00.html|title="The man who came from nowhere to bankroll the Liberal Democrats"|publisher=''The Times''|accessdate=2008-07-29}}</ref>

Specified Associated Organisations (SAOs) review and input policies, representing groups including: [[ethnic minorities]] (EMLD]),<ref>http://ethnic-minority.libdems.org/index.html</ref> women (WLD),<ref>http://wld.org.uk/</ref> the LGBT community ([[Delga]]),<ref>http://www.lgbt.libdems.org.uk</ref> youth and students ([[Liberal Youth]]), engineers and scientists (ALDES),<ref>http://www.aldes.org.uk</ref> parliamentary candidates (PCA)<ref>http://www.parliamentary.org.uk/tikiwiki/tiki-read_article.php?articleId=1</ref> and local [[councillor]]s (ALDC).<ref>http://www.aldc.org/</ref> Others can become Associated Organisations (AOs) as pressure groups in the party, such as the Green Liberal Democrats,<ref>http://www.green.libdems.org.uk/</ref> Liberal Democrats Online<ref>http://www.online.libdems.org/</ref> and the Liberal Democrat Disability Association.<ref>http://www.disabilitylibdems.org.uk/</ref> The National Union of Liberal Clubs (NULC)represents Liberal Social Clubs which encourages recreational institutions where the promotion of the party can take place. 

Like the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]], the Lib Dems organise in [[Northern Ireland]], though they do not contest elections in the province: they work with the [[Alliance Party of Northern Ireland]], ''de facto'' agreeing to support the Alliance in elections.<ref name="allianceNI">{{cite web|year = 2001|url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/1545103.stm|title =Alliance Party faces uphill battle|publisher =[[BBC]]|accessdate =2008-03-21}}</ref> There is a small separate local party of the Lib Dems in Northern Ireland. Several individuals, including Alliance Party leader [[David Ford]], hold membership of both parties. Alliance members of the [[House of Lords]] take the Lib Dem [[whip (politics)|whip]] on non-Northern Ireland issues, and the Alliance Party usually has a stall at Lib Dem [[party conference]]s.

The party is a member of [[Liberal International]] and the [[European Liberal Democrat and Reform Party]], and their 11 MEPs sit in the [[Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe]] (ALDE) group in the [[European Parliament]].

===Internal factions===
Liberal Democrats can be classified into two factions <U+2013> social and market liberals <U+2013> which are unrelated to membership of the party's predecessors <U+2013> many social liberals (including [[Paddy Ashdown]]) were former Liberal MPs, and some market liberals (such as [[Vincent Cable]]) were from the SDP.

'''[[Social liberal]]s''' have dominated the party since its formation. Drawing inspiration from [[David Lloyd George]], [[William Beveridge]] and [[John Maynard Keynes]], this wing  advocates the [[welfare state]], higher taxation and public spending, government regulation to protect consumers, employees and the environment, and support [[civil liberties]] and [[human rights]]. Social liberals include [[Paul Holmes (politician)|Paul Holmes]], [[Norman Baker]] and [[Simon Hughes]].

The '''[[market liberal]]''' or '''[[libertarian]]''' wing shares with social liberals a belief in basic civil and political freedoms (''[[negative liberty|negative freedoms]]''). However, where social liberals argue that the state should provide social and economic rights to its citizens (''[[positive liberty|positive freedoms]]''), market liberals are non-interventionist and are critical of government's ability to increase freedom. This often manifests itself as support for greater [[economic freedom]], causing tension between the two wings. Many MPs from this wing contributed to the ''[[The Orange Book: Reclaiming Liberalism|Orange Book]]'' (2004),<ref name="orangebook">{{cite web|year = 2004|url =http://www.bonkers.hall.btinternet.co.uk/liberator.html|title =Orange Blossom|publisher =[[Liberator (magazine)|Liberator]]|accessdate =2008-03-26}}</ref> a collection of essays intended to spark debate on a greater role for free-market liberalism in policy. Some party donors, journalists and party officials back this wing of the party.<ref name="freemarket">{{cite web|year = 2004|url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/3621340.stm|title = Lib Dems call for pro-market move|publisher =[[BBC]]|accessdate =2008-01-28}}</ref> Leading market liberals in the party include [[Vince Cable]], [[David Laws]] and [[Nick Clegg]].<ref name="orangebook" />

